According to a recent Gallup poll, 70% of the members of the House of
Representatives oppose limiting the number of congressional terms,
while almost two- thirds of the public support the idea.  Franking
privileges and campaign finance laws make defeating an incumbent very
difficult, with 96% of incumbents re-elected over the past three
elections.  Also, one in four incumbents this year will have no major
party opposition.  This trend is spreading to the Senate.  Since
presidents are limited to two terms, political power has shifted to
the legislature.  Congressional careerism has become the norm, and
some want a constitutional amendment to limit terms.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ911106-0109"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="I">   

While some Democrats claim term limits are a "right-wing" crusade,
this author (John Fund) believes support from the liberal and
Democratic sphere is increasing.  Polls show Americans back term
limits by 75% to 21% nationwide.  One reason is that term limits would
open up politics to people--minorities and women--now excluded from
office.  Some past Democratic leaders were cited as supporting the
idea, but the party "apparatchiks" remain against it.  Some
journalists favor term limits voicing a need for new blood and the end
of professional politicians.  Fund does not believe enacting term
limits will be easy.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
