Nelson Polsby does not believe term limits will give their proponents
what they want.  Term limitation will not decrease the influence of
interest groups and their money because new candidates need even more
money to get recognition.  Inexperienced legislators must learn their
job from the legislative staff, bureaucrats and lobbyists, thus
shifting the power from the elected officials.  We should vote poor
performers out.  Terms limits would only throw the good out with the
bad.  He also fears the main supporters of term limits are those who
are assuming non-incumbents are easier to beat or buy.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA101090-0017"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="I">   

Ross Baker equates term limits to burning down the house to get rid of
the rats.  He believe the recurring temptation to legislate vengeance
on adversaries will backfire.  Oklahoma has limited state lawmakers to
12 years' service.  This will create more amateurs who will be
controlled by governors and bureaucrats and more vulnerable to
corruption.  Additionally, office holders will not have a stake in
their job and will be more concerned with their next job.  Lobbyists
and legislative staffs will be celebrating the guaranteed influx of
inexperienced office holders.  Baker considers term limits illogical
and wrong, and an insult to the voters.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910718-0143"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="I">   

T.K. Wetherel does not believe that the Federalists Alexander Hamilton
and James Madison supported term limits.  Limits were included in the
failed Articles of Confederation and rejected by the Constitutional
Convention and the First Congress.  Hamilton reasoned term limitations
on the presidency would diminish the inducements to good behavior.
Madison wrote that members of Congress in long-standing could become
masters of the public business.  Not the Federalists, but the
out-of-power opposition wanted limits.  With term limits, key
legislation, such as the 1850 Compromise and civil- rights bills, may
not have been enacted and Medicare and Social Security may not have
been protected.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ911030-0008"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="I">   

Albert Hunt reports that pollsters have found the public losing
confidence in the electoral system and the Congress.  People want more
representation and this is the impetus behind the momentum for
limiting terms of lawmakers.  Hunt believes these limits would result
in more power going to the unelected staff and lobbyists.  Voters
should never be prevented from electing who they think is best.  Other
solutions might be eliminating some of Congress' perquisites and a
fundamental overhaul of the committee system.  Legislators now are put
on a committee and stay there, becoming stale and locked into outdated
approaches.  The length of committee assignments should be
limited.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ911224-0085"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="I">   

Robert Barro discusses his surprise that some free market advocates,
with their faith in the self-interested consumer, support term limits.
The free marketers claim incumbent politicians have an unfair
advantage, 95% of the incumbents were re-elected, and a citizen
Congress would result in better government.  Barro believes decreasing
the excessive incentive of maintaining a legislator's seniority status
may be a better solution.  Legislative branch term limits are an
attempt to shift power back to the executive branch, now subjected to
limits.  Barro believes ending executive limits would be a better
solution, especially since there is no evidence that they improved
governing.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d54"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA102190-0045"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="I">   

Californians were asked what would state government be like by 1996 if
two propositions to limit terms of statewide officeholders and state
legislators, on California's November ballot, are passed.  Individuals
felt there would be all new faces and the people would have more
control, politics would not be a profession, expertise would come from
the citizenry, and candidates would be more dependent on the party for
financing and less dependent of the special interests.  On the other
side, individuals felt it would be clear that amateurs can't handle
the complex job, everyone is a lame duck from the beginning,
minorities would lose, and power would go to the executive branch and
bureaucrats.</SUM>
